noneofyer42businessbub wrote:

&gt; What is the best/recommended way to add enhancements to the
&gt; framework&#39;s
&gt; Assert class?  In other words, how does one add exta assertion
&gt; methods (which
&gt; are more specialized than the current ones) to the framework?
&gt;
&gt; A. Should one first create a sub-class of Assert then change
&gt; TestCase&#39;s parent
&gt; to be one&#39;s new Assert sub-class?
&gt;
&gt; B. Or should one tack on one&#39;s custom Assert class to  exterior of
&gt; the
&gt; framework (i.e.-make one&#39;s custom Assert class a sub-class TestCase
&gt; then
&gt; make one&#39;s unit tests a sub-class of the custom Assert class)?
&gt;

If the custom assertions are used by many test cases, I&#39;ll typically use this
approach:

    public class BaseTestCase extends TestCase {

        public void assertSomething(Something a, Something b) {
            // ...
        }

        // more custom asserts
    }

    public class TestCaseA extends BaseTestCase {

        public void testSomethingForA() {
            assertSomething(a, b);
        }
    }

    public class TestCaseB extends BaseTestCase {

        public void testSomethingForB() {
            assertSomething(a, b);
        }
    }

This works well if many test cases will end up using the custom assertion.

If the custom assertions are used in only one test case, I&#39;ll just defined
those assertions within the specialized test case itself.  This gives me to
option to refactor them into a base test case later if necessary.

You could also define a separate assertion utility class with static
assertion methods, then use it with multiple test cases.

